1
00:00:00,320 --> 00:00:06,560
Building trading bots and indicators used 
to be for tech geniuses. Well, not anymore! 

2
00:00:06,560 --> 00:00:10,960
I have zero coding experience 
and I’m creating my OWN trading  

3
00:00:10,960 --> 00:00:17,840
bots in TradingView… in just a few minutes!
So today I want to help you create and optimize  

4
00:00:17,840 --> 00:00:25,680
your own indicators and strategies in Tradingview, 
using AI, without any experience in programming! 

5
00:00:25,680 --> 00:00:27,680
THIS is the ultimate shortcut to smarter trading!
 
So let me walk you through the  

6
00:00:27,680 --> 00:00:32,560
entire process step by step.
I’m using Claude AI on Poe app,  

7
00:00:32,560 --> 00:00:38,320
but you can use any AI model you like.
I sometimes switch to Deepseek or O1  

8
00:00:38,320 --> 00:00:43,920
models when I get several errors in a 
row, but the process remains the same. 

9
00:00:43,920 --> 00:00:48,480
Let’s start with the most critical 
part: crafting the starting prompt. 

10
00:00:48,480 --> 00:00:54,960
Your trading bot's capabilities depend entirely 
on how well you structure these instructions! 

11
00:00:54,960 --> 00:01:00,640
So first let's create a prompt that 
turns your AI into a trading agent. 

12
00:01:00,640 --> 00:01:07,280
Use this prompt: “I want you to be my trading 
assistant. You're an expert in trading and coding,  

13
00:01:07,280 --> 00:01:13,520
especially Pine Script 6 for TradingView. You 
can create any indicator or strategy I need,  

14
00:01:13,520 --> 00:01:18,320
with clean code and few errors.”
 
Ok, now let's make your assistant  

15
00:01:18,320 --> 00:01:24,320
even smarter by feeding it more information 
about your specific trading preferences. This  

16
00:01:24,320 --> 00:01:30,960
step is crucial for making the AI truly yours.
Tell your bot about your preferred markets:  

17
00:01:30,960 --> 00:01:37,680
do you prefer trading stocks, forex, crypto?
Tell your bot about your typical timeframes: do  

18
00:01:37,680 --> 00:01:44,480
you enjoy scalping, day trading or swing trading?
You’ll also mention your risk tolerance, your  

19
00:01:44,480 --> 00:01:51,840
trading style, like trend following or breakouts.
For instance, you might say: "I primarily swing  

20
00:01:51,840 --> 00:01:58,000
trade stocks using price action methods 
on 4 hour charts. I prefer to use minimal  

21
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:03,520
indicators and focus on market structure."
The more context you provide, the more  

22
00:02:03,520 --> 00:02:08,320
tailored the advice becomes.
 
 
 
After creating your assistant,  

23
00:02:08,320 --> 00:02:15,120
it's time to see if it works as expected.
Let’s start with something easy. I use exponential  

24
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:22,880
moving averages a lot in my trading, and I want to 
ask my AI assistant to help me color-code an EMA. 

25
00:02:22,880 --> 00:02:27,520
I want it green when price is above 
it, and red when price is below it. 

26
00:02:27,520 --> 00:02:34,240
We'll ask it to modify the basic EMA code 
to change colors based on price position. 

27
00:02:34,240 --> 00:02:40,880
Now we'll copy the standard EMA code from 
TradingView and paste it into our chat. 

28
00:02:40,880 --> 00:02:47,040
Then we’ll wait for the assistant to do its magic.
Nothing groundbreaking yet, we're just making that  

29
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:51,040
information more visible.
Okey, we’ve got our code. 

30
00:02:51,040 --> 00:02:56,800
Now let’s implement it in TradingView.
You open your TradingView chart and look for the  

31
00:02:56,800 --> 00:03:02,880
Pine Editor button at the bottom of your screen.
Click it to open the coding interface. When the  

32
00:03:02,880 --> 00:03:07,760
editor opens, you'll see a blank 
canvas or some template code. 

33
00:03:07,760 --> 00:03:13,120
You just click on "New" and select 
"Indicator" from the dropdown menu. 

34
00:03:13,120 --> 00:03:18,960
This creates a fresh Pine Script file. 
Don’t forget to delete any template code,  

35
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:26,160
then paste the code your AI assistant provided.
Then give your script a name and save it. 

36
00:03:26,160 --> 00:03:31,040
Next, you press "Add to Chart" 
to see your creation in action. 

37
00:03:31,040 --> 00:03:35,440
If there are no errors, your 
indicator will appear on your chart. 

38
00:03:35,440 --> 00:03:41,360
If there are errors, and you will encounter 
them, just copy them or make a print screen,  

39
00:03:41,360 --> 00:03:47,840
and ask the assistant to fix the errors 
and rewrite the entire code again. 

40
00:03:47,840 --> 00:03:53,520
So this indicator seems to work as 
intended. The visual feedback is instant. 

41
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:58,160
When candles close above the EMA, 
the line turns green. When price  

42
00:03:58,160 --> 00:04:04,560
dips below, it immediately switches to red.
Let’s check if this works on any timeframe.  

43
00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:10,560
It does, so this works as expected.
 
 
 
 
 
 
Now let's continue with something  

44
00:04:10,560 --> 00:04:16,080
practical involving pivot points.
Pivot points are powerful tools, but sometimes  

45
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:23,200
I want them to be calculated on lower timeframes.
So I want to ask my AI assistant to modify the  

46
00:04:23,200 --> 00:04:28,000
pivot point indicator, to show 
hourly pivot levels, since daily  

47
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:35,040
is the lowest timeframe available by default.
Fun fact, ten years ago, I paid a programmer  

48
00:04:35,040 --> 00:04:42,160
$200 to code this exact indicator for me.
So, we'll ask our AI assistant to modify  

49
00:04:42,160 --> 00:04:48,400
the standard pivot point indicator code, 
to calculate pivots on an hourly timeframe. 

50
00:04:48,400 --> 00:04:52,080
This should be a simple change 
in the timeframe reference. 

51
00:04:52,080 --> 00:04:58,400
So we'll copy the pivot point code from 
TradingView and paste it into our chat. 

52
00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:04,400
The classic pivot point calculation shows 
daily support and resistance levels, that help  

53
00:05:04,400 --> 00:05:10,720
identify price combinations quickly and easily.
But I want them displayed on an hourly basis.  

54
00:05:10,720 --> 00:05:15,520
I want pivot points to confirm 
intraday bias in the markets. 

55
00:05:15,520 --> 00:05:20,160
I like to compare the current trading 
day's central pivot with the previous  

56
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:26,880
day's to establish bias, and then confirm 
that bias based on where price opens. 

57
00:05:26,880 --> 00:05:32,040
Having this on an hourly timeframe will 
give me more granular entry opportunities. 

58
00:05:32,040 --> 00:05:37,760
Ok, the modified code came back quickly.
Now let's head over to TradingView,  

59
00:05:37,760 --> 00:05:41,280
and open the Pine Editor.
Again, we'll clear out the  

60
00:05:41,280 --> 00:05:47,360
default code and paste in the modified 
pivot point script from my assistant. 

61
00:05:47,360 --> 00:05:51,040
We can immediately see the 
hourly pivot points appear. 

62
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:56,480
Each horizontal line represents a key 
support or resistance level, calculated  

63
00:05:56,480 --> 00:06:00,960
from the previous hour's levels.
The indicator works beautifully,  

64
00:06:00,960 --> 00:06:06,160
showing clear pivot points that 
align perfectly with price reactions. 

65
00:06:06,160 --> 00:06:11,600
I can use these pivot levels alongside 
other tools for confirmation. 

66
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:16,000
Also, when you make your own tools, 
don’t forget to check if they work  

67
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:21,760
on different symbols and timeframes.
Testing it on various charts confirms  

68
00:06:21,760 --> 00:06:27,440
it's working perfectly across the board.
Honestly, I'm amazed at how much things  

69
00:06:27,440 --> 00:06:33,360
have changed. In the past, getting this kind 
of custom indicator made would have cost me  

70
00:06:33,360 --> 00:06:40,000
$200, required many back-and-forth emails 
and taken a full two weeks to complete. 

71
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:46,080
But today? The entire process took less 
than 3 minutes from start to finish!
 
 
  

72
00:06:46,080 --> 00:06:52,640
Now, let's create a more complex indicator. I 
want a tool that highlights engulfing candles,  

73
00:06:52,640 --> 00:06:56,480
with their volume higher 
than the previous 5 candles. 

74
00:06:56,480 --> 00:07:02,880
Engulfing candlestick patterns are powerful 
signals, especially when confirmed by volume. 

75
00:07:02,880 --> 00:07:07,760
They occur when a larger candle 
completely engulfs the previous candle. 

76
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:13,760
When combined with volume analysis, these 
patterns become even more significant. 

77
00:07:13,760 --> 00:07:18,000
I'll ask my AI assistant to 
create a custom indicator  

78
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:23,680
for these high-volume engulfing patterns.
This should be straightforward since we just  

79
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:30,640
need to check two main conditions: the engulfing 
pattern formation and the volume comparison. 

80
00:07:30,640 --> 00:07:34,400
First, let's define what 
makes an engulfing pattern. 

81
00:07:34,400 --> 00:07:39,920
For a bullish engulfing, the current candle 
must be green and its body must completely  

82
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:45,680
engulf the previous red candle's body.
For a bearish engulfing, the current candle  

83
00:07:45,680 --> 00:07:51,760
must be red and its body must completely 
engulf the previous green candle's body. 

84
00:07:51,760 --> 00:07:58,080
The wide spread of these engulfing candles 
sends a clear signal with one message: sentiment  

85
00:07:58,080 --> 00:08:05,200
is STRONG, either bullishly or bearishly.
So we'll ask our assistant to write code that  

86
00:08:05,200 --> 00:08:11,440
identifies these patterns and checks if the 
volume is higher than the previous 5 candles. 

87
00:08:11,440 --> 00:08:17,920
This is a key condition. Volume is crucial 
because it validates the price action. If we  

88
00:08:17,920 --> 00:08:23,760
see a large engulfing candle but the volume 
is below average, it's a warning signal. 

89
00:08:23,760 --> 00:08:29,680
Only when volume rises with the price pattern, 
it shows real market strength or weakness. 

90
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:34,960
Ok, the assistant has finished the 
code so let's head over to TradingView. 

91
00:08:34,960 --> 00:08:39,920
We'll clear out any default code 
and paste in our new indicator. 

92
00:08:40,480 --> 00:08:46,720
Now let’s see the indicator in action.
Ok, so the indicator works by placing colored  

93
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:53,120
markers on candles that meet our criteria.
Looking at some examples on the chart,  

94
00:08:53,120 --> 00:08:58,320
we can see how these high-volume patterns 
often mark significant turning points,  

95
00:08:58,320 --> 00:09:02,080
or continuation signals.
Testing on different  

96
00:09:02,080 --> 00:09:07,680
timeframes shows the indicator works 
well across various chart settings. 

97
00:09:07,680 --> 00:09:13,760
One interesting pattern I'm noticing is that 
many of the bearish engulfing candles with high  

98
00:09:13,760 --> 00:09:21,520
volume appear at resistance levels, while bullish 
engulfing candles with high volume often appear  

99
00:09:21,520 --> 00:09:28,960
at support. This aligns with what we know about 
volume profile analysis – it takes effort for the  

100
00:09:28,960 --> 00:09:35,440
market to move away from established levels, 
and this effort shows up as increased volume. 

101
00:09:35,440 --> 00:09:38,720
I could also look for additional confirmation,  

102
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:44,320
like adding a moving average or another 
indicator. But the main condition,  

103
00:09:44,320 --> 00:09:49,760
price action and volume, is in place.
So I will save this indicator because  

104
00:09:49,760 --> 00:09:56,720
will be particularly useful for spotting potential 
continuation and reversals after a strong move. 

105
00:09:56,720 --> 00:10:02,560
When combined with support/resistance 
levels and other volume profile analysis,  

106
00:10:02,560 --> 00:10:07,600
it becomes a powerful edge for 
entering trades with conviction.
  

107
00:10:07,600 --> 00:10:12,560
Now let’s increase the difficulty notch!
Let's create a momentum indicator that  

108
00:10:12,560 --> 00:10:16,960
measures the strength of price 
action over the last X candles. 

109
00:10:16,960 --> 00:10:22,640
This indicator will count recent bars 
and measure the body of bullish candles,  

110
00:10:22,640 --> 00:10:29,120
versus bearish candles, giving us a clear 
picture of which side is winning the battle. 

111
00:10:29,120 --> 00:10:33,840
The body of a candle tells us about 
strength - a long body shows strong  

112
00:10:33,840 --> 00:10:39,680
commitment from either buyers or sellers.
When consecutive bodies become larger,  

113
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:45,840
it shows increasing momentum, while 
smaller bodies indicate slowing momentum. 

114
00:10:45,840 --> 00:10:51,920
That's exactly what our indicator will track.
I'll ask the assistant to write a custom indicator  

115
00:10:51,920 --> 00:10:58,800
that adds up the body sizes of bullish and 
bearish candles over a look back period. 

116
00:10:58,800 --> 00:11:03,440
This will give us a momentum 
score for each side of the market. 

117
00:11:03,440 --> 00:11:07,920
The size of these bodies matters greatly.
Remember that in every bar, the same  

118
00:11:07,920 --> 00:11:13,120
number of contracts or shares are traded.
The only reason a bar ends with a higher  

119
00:11:13,120 --> 00:11:18,480
price is that buyers were more committed 
and aggressive than sellers. The reverse  

120
00:11:18,480 --> 00:11:22,560
is true for bearish candles.
So the body size directly  

121
00:11:22,560 --> 00:11:27,920
reflects the strength behind the move.
That’s why I want the indicator to loop through  

122
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:36,000
the last X candles, to measure each body size, and 
to add them to either a bullish or bearish total. 

123
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:42,800
We have the code, now let's head to 
TradingView and paste our new indicator. 

124
00:11:42,800 --> 00:11:48,400
No errors when we add it to chart!
We can see three lines appear - one  

125
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:54,400
for bullish momentum, one for bearish 
momentum, and one showing the ratio. 

126
00:11:54,400 --> 00:11:59,680
Let’s hide the ratio for now, and 
let’s focus on the main lines. 

127
00:11:59,680 --> 00:12:05,040
Looking at the chart with our new indicator, 
we can spot some interesting patterns. 

128
00:12:05,040 --> 00:12:11,040
When the bullish line rises sharply while 
the bearish line remains flat, we see price  

129
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:18,720
making strong upward moves. This aligns with 
a well know candlestick analysis principle:  

130
00:12:18,720 --> 00:12:25,360
a wide body represents strong market sentiment.
This tool works well with the concept of  

131
00:12:25,360 --> 00:12:30,080
consecutive candles increasing 
or decreasing in size. 

132
00:12:30,080 --> 00:12:37,040
When we see the momentum lines diverging, meaning 
bullish line rising while bearish line falling,  

133
00:12:37,040 --> 00:12:44,000
it often corresponds to consecutive candles 
getting larger in the direction of the trend. 

134
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:48,080
This pattern frequently appears 
at the start of strong moves. 

135
00:12:48,080 --> 00:12:52,160
If the bullish line starts to 
flatten after a strong rise,  

136
00:12:52,160 --> 00:12:58,720
it suggests buyers are losing control - 
an early warning of a potential reversal. 

137
00:12:58,720 --> 00:13:05,840
When the bearish line flattens after a decline, 
it signals sellers may be losing control. 

138
00:13:05,840 --> 00:13:12,160
Volume validates price action, so as a next step 
we might enhance this indicator by factoring  

139
00:13:12,160 --> 00:13:19,280
in volume. But even in its current form, it 
provides valuable insight into market momentum. 

140
00:13:19,280 --> 00:13:25,600
I like using it on the 4-hour time frame 
and I must say, this is pretty accurate. 

141
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:33,120
Perfect to identify when momentum is slowing or 
rising. I can predict the next 4-hour candle with  

142
00:13:33,120 --> 00:13:37,600
a pretty high accuracy using it.
You may find this useless,  

143
00:13:37,600 --> 00:13:43,840
but for me, this indicator is amazing.
By measuring the relative strength of buyers  

144
00:13:43,840 --> 00:13:50,160
versus sellers over the last several candles, 
this little tool helps me "read the momentum",  

145
00:13:50,160 --> 00:13:55,280
based on actual price action.
 
 
Now let’s create a trading strategy  

146
00:13:55,280 --> 00:14:00,080
using the indicator we just built.
The rules are simple: enter long  

147
00:14:00,080 --> 00:14:06,960
when bullish strength crosses above bearish 
strength, and price is above the 100 SMA. 

148
00:14:06,960 --> 00:14:14,640
Enter short when bearish strength crosses above 
bullish strength and price is below the 100 SMA. 

149
00:14:14,640 --> 00:14:19,120
The strategy logic is to check for 
crossovers between the bullish and  

150
00:14:19,120 --> 00:14:25,680
bearish strength lines, while confirming 
the price position relative to the 100 SMA. 

151
00:14:25,680 --> 00:14:30,000
When all conditions align, the 
strategy enters a position. 

152
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:36,240
When I first ran the code, I got an error.
This happens often when building strategies,  

153
00:14:37,040 --> 00:14:42,320
so I just copied the error message 
and asked the assistant to fix it. 

154
00:14:42,320 --> 00:14:47,840
We went back and forth a few times, 
fixing bugs and refining the logic. 

155
00:14:47,840 --> 00:14:53,680
One issue was with the crossover detection - 
we needed to make sure we were only entering  

156
00:14:53,680 --> 00:14:59,920
on the bar where the crossover happened, at 
the candle close, not in the middle of it. 

157
00:14:59,920 --> 00:15:07,680
After a few iterations, we had working code. I 
pasted it into TradingView's and ran a backtest. 

158
00:15:07,680 --> 00:15:12,400
I checked if the strategy was taking 
trades at exactly the right moments,  

159
00:15:12,400 --> 00:15:18,400
as intended - entering longs when bullish 
candles started overpowering bearish  

160
00:15:18,400 --> 00:15:25,760
ones, above the 100 SMA, and shorts when 
bearish candles dominated below the 100 SMA. 

161
00:15:25,760 --> 00:15:33,120
The backtest results were promising. The strategy 
showed positive returns and a decent win rate. 

162
00:15:33,120 --> 00:15:39,040
The best results were on the 30 minutes 
time frame, with the 200 SMA as a filter,  

163
00:15:39,040 --> 00:15:43,680
and the indicator measuring the 
strength of the last 10 candles. 

164
00:15:43,680 --> 00:15:48,800
This makes sense because we're essentially 
trading with the more dominant market force,  

165
00:15:48,800 --> 00:15:54,320
while also respecting the overall 
trend direction with the SMA filter. 

166
00:15:54,320 --> 00:16:00,800
Then I asked the assistant to assess the backtest 
results. And it noted that the strategy was  

167
00:16:00,800 --> 00:16:08,640
profitable but had a relatively low Sharpe ratio.
The Sharpe ratio measures return relative to risk,  

168
00:16:08,640 --> 00:16:12,560
so this suggested our returns 
weren't quite high enough,  

169
00:16:12,560 --> 00:16:19,600
compared to the volatility we were experiencing.
The Sortino ratio, however, was relatively high.  

170
00:16:19,600 --> 00:16:24,640
This is important because the Sortino 
ratio focuses specifically on downside  

171
00:16:24,640 --> 00:16:30,400
risk - the bad volatility that hurts 
us - rather than all volatility. 

172
00:16:30,400 --> 00:16:38,160
A high Sortino ratio means our strategy is making 
money, while controlling drawdowns effectively. 

173
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:42,640
Of course, I can go deeper with the 
adjustments, but you get the point! 

174
00:16:42,640 --> 00:16:47,520
The assistant suggested we might 
improve performance by refining entry  

175
00:16:47,520 --> 00:16:55,200
and exit conditions or adjusting position sizing.
One specific recommendation was to test increasing  

176
00:16:55,200 --> 00:17:00,880
position size, since the strategy appeared 
reliable enough to potentially handle larger  

177
00:17:00,880 --> 00:17:07,760
positions, without significantly increasing risk.
What makes this strategy smart is the fact it  

178
00:17:07,760 --> 00:17:13,440
doesn't try to predict the future. It just 
measures what's happening right now - which side  

179
00:17:13,440 --> 00:17:19,920
is showing more strength - and trades accordingly.
We're not trying to guess; we're responding to  

180
00:17:19,920 --> 00:17:23,360
actual market behavior.
What I like about this  

181
00:17:23,360 --> 00:17:29,440
trading bot is that it doesn't rely on complex 
indicators. It simply measures what's happening  

182
00:17:29,440 --> 00:17:35,280
with price action - the size of bullish 
versus bearish candles - and trades when  

183
00:17:35,280 --> 00:17:41,840
a clear advantage appears for one side.
The SMA filter adds another dimension by  

184
00:17:41,840 --> 00:17:48,880
keeping us on the right side of the larger trend.
Overall, the assistant concluded this was a decent  

185
00:17:48,880 --> 00:17:54,080
combination of high returns, high win rate, 
and controlled risk. So I’ll keep adjusting  

186
00:17:54,080 --> 00:17:59,600
and back testing it in the future!
 
 
Here’s another tool I’ve created. I  

187
00:17:59,600 --> 00:18:04,000
wanted an indicator to highlight 
the trading range for each day. 

188
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:09,760
This Daily Boxes indicator tracks each 
trading day with colored boxes. It want  

189
00:18:09,760 --> 00:18:16,880
to see daily highs and lows at a glance, which 
is critical for understanding market structure. 

190
00:18:16,880 --> 00:18:20,880
This tool provides a broader 
perspective of price movements,  

191
00:18:20,880 --> 00:18:28,160
and helps me identify key levels and trends.
 
Green boxes show bullish days, where price  

192
00:18:28,160 --> 00:18:32,720
closed higher than it opened.
Red boxes show bearish days,  

193
00:18:32,720 --> 00:18:38,720
where price closed lower than it opened.
What makes this indicator powerful is how  

194
00:18:38,720 --> 00:18:46,160
it lets me quickly see the sequence of daily highs 
and lows. When analyzing charts, I pay attention  

195
00:18:46,160 --> 00:18:52,320
to the number of up boxes or red boxes.
This helps determine the strength of  

196
00:18:52,320 --> 00:18:58,400
buy or sell scenarios. The boxes make 
this pattern recognition much easier.

197
00:18:58,960 --> 00:19:05,440
I’ve asked the assistant to let me choose how many 
days I want to display, and what colors to use. 

198
00:19:05,440 --> 00:19:11,200
Then I wanted a clear function to detect when 
a new trading day begins. This is important  

199
00:19:11,200 --> 00:19:18,320
because we need to know when to start a new box.
I had a few problems here as I got many errors,  

200
00:19:18,320 --> 00:19:25,360
but in the end, the indicator worked as I wanted.
Each time a new day starts, the indicator creates  

201
00:19:25,360 --> 00:19:31,280
a fresh box starting at the current bar.
The box extends to the right and gets  

202
00:19:31,280 --> 00:19:38,480
updated throughout the day as price makes new 
highs or lows. The box color changes based  

203
00:19:38,480 --> 00:19:43,920
on whether price is currently above 
or below the day's opening price.
  

204
00:19:43,920 --> 00:19:50,640
From a price action perspective, these boxes 
help me identify the premium and discount zones  

205
00:19:50,640 --> 00:19:55,280
that are so important in trading.
The daily highs and lows marked  

206
00:19:55,280 --> 00:20:01,840
by these boxes become significant levels.
Previous daily highs offer short-term resistance  

207
00:20:01,840 --> 00:20:08,480
levels, if price reaches those levels again.
Similarly, the lowest low traded in the  

208
00:20:08,480 --> 00:20:14,560
previous day can offer significant support.
These levels are precisely what banks and  

209
00:20:14,560 --> 00:20:19,440
institutions often monitor for 
buying and selling interest. 

210
00:20:19,440 --> 00:20:24,960
By having them clearly boxed on your chart, 
I can position myself strategically for  

211
00:20:24,960 --> 00:20:28,800
these potential moves.
 
The indicator also helps  

212
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:33,120
identify order flow patterns.
In a bullish order flow,  

213
00:20:33,120 --> 00:20:40,560
buyers dominate the market, driving prices higher, 
and the market tends to seek buyside liquidity,  

214
00:20:40,560 --> 00:20:44,640
above the previous day's highs.
You'll see this as a series of  

215
00:20:44,640 --> 00:20:50,000
green boxes with higher highs.
Conversely, in bearish order flow,  

216
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:57,520
sellers dominate, and the market seeks sellside 
liquidity, below the previous day's lows, visible  

217
00:20:57,520 --> 00:21:05,280
as a sequence of red boxes with lower lows.
With these boxes, you can spot when a day's range  

218
00:21:05,280 --> 00:21:12,800
is much smaller or larger than previous days, 
indicating potential changes in market sentiment.
  

219
00:21:13,440 --> 00:21:20,080
Another tool I’ve created is an Average Daily 
Range indicator. This helps me understand market  

220
00:21:20,080 --> 00:21:27,040
volatility and how much a market has moved 
today, compared to its typical daily movement. 

221
00:21:27,040 --> 00:21:33,920
This tool answers key questions: Is today more 
or less volatile than normal? Has the market  

222
00:21:33,920 --> 00:21:39,520
already reached its typical daily range? 
Is there still room for price to move?
  

223
00:21:39,520 --> 00:21:46,560
The ADR concept is rooted in market volatility 
analysis. Markets trade with an average daily  

224
00:21:46,560 --> 00:21:52,000
range that varies by instrument.
And this variation is critical for  

225
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:58,320
setting realistic profit targets and stops.
 
The code creates a simple yet powerful  

226
00:21:58,320 --> 00:22:03,440
indicator that calculates the average 
range over a set number of days,  

227
00:22:03,440 --> 00:22:09,920
then compares today's range to that average.
I wanted the indicator to have a user input  

228
00:22:09,920 --> 00:22:15,040
for how many days to include in 
the calculation, usually 20 days. 

229
00:22:15,040 --> 00:22:22,240
It also asks for a pips multiplier, which helps 
adjust the decimal places for different markets. 

230
00:22:22,240 --> 00:22:28,320
It also calculates what percentage of the 
average range today's move represents. 

231
00:22:28,320 --> 00:22:34,320
This information is crucial for my trading 
decisions, especially with my profit targets. 

232
00:22:34,320 --> 00:22:41,360
For instance if today's range is already at 
95% of the average, I might expect limited  

233
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:49,040
further movement and consider taking profits.
But if the ADR is only at 30%, there might  

234
00:22:49,040 --> 00:22:54,800
still be substantial movement ahead.
 
I can also use the ADR to set targets  

235
00:22:54,800 --> 00:23:00,960
based on the previous day's high and 
low, using the daily boxes indicator. 

236
00:23:00,960 --> 00:23:05,360
For example, if today's range is 
small compared to the average,  

237
00:23:05,360 --> 00:23:12,320
the previous day's high or low might be realistic 
targets, depending on the trend direction. 

238
00:23:12,320 --> 00:23:18,000
I wanted this tool because instead of using 
arbitrary numbers, I want to use the market's  

239
